darling Gopher -Doris and I went ashore at Asyut, under the escort of Hareem to take a drive through the city. The Beduin could not get close to the shore so we were landed in the felucca with six Nubians rowing it with a man-of-war's-men precision. We lnnded at the foot 00 steep, high bank done in rough masonry, and before I had time to wondE how on earth l was to climb it I found myself at the top.A trusty mariner at each elbow had wafted me thither. There's never the slight full, -a god, a single word from the person in command and the thing done as if by magic. It was the same when we returned from our Asyut: spree. The Beduin and the felucca had moved up the stream to B spot t even the felucca couldn't make n landing. ~ word from Hareem <end D. r I were picked up deftly, carried through the water and set down gentle into the bout. It was market day in Asyut and the entire popul tion was Apparently in the streets. We drove through the bazaar end s market where men, women, children, bulls, camels, donkeys were in one! grand mass. It is a large, important, rich town, with many elaborate; houses belonging to natives, and during our entire drive we snw~ not J single white person.
In spite of the delights in store for us I hote to have this he~venl voyage end. To all the enchnntments of the shores have Intely been added the most wonderful flocks of birds. The Sister-Kittie :Innounce yesterda.y when we joined her on deck that a flight of at least a
thousand crnnes had passed overhead, and not nIl our efforts could m,
her come down one crnne.I myself connted sixty-two pelicans sitting on a sandbnr. And today we sailed by close to Kasz-es-Snynd ("the Hnnter's Castle")~ n. What easily might be n castle is nothing more her less that n colossol pigeon-honse. Hn.reds of thonsands of pigeong were perching on the battlements or flying abont then, n. little flocks here hastening home to them from all directions. They are bred in this land ns mnch for their droppings, which make n mnch-prized fertilizer, as for food. (That's n herrid son.ing sentence bnt yon will n.erstand What I mess). On the West bank of the river, opposite the Hnnter's Castle, is the little town of Hon where for 53 years Shieck Selim sat stark naked on the bank of the Nile. He died a few years ago, and they bnilt a tomb on his sitting place to Which the natives make pilgrimages. clothes seem rather lightly esteemed in Egypt. If the day is Warm the Shadnf workers wear practically the same garb as the Ap~che Indinn, n. their beantifnl bodies look like bronze. We were passing qnite close to the shere when a gentleman bon.ed down the banks, yanked off his one and only garment and proceeded to do is lan.ry work in the Nile.
Sunday -22nd December. The Beduin, Luxor. At noon yesterday and a day soaked in sunshine awe came in sight of Luxor, and n short time thereafter had reached its outskirts, and from the window of a dnhabyo tied to the east book the plensapt, tousled heed of Nicols, ll English artist, bowed and called greetings to Cousin Theodore. Post some charming looking hotels we slipped, catching glimpses in between of the most beautiful columns of the Temple of Luxor, past the Winter Palace Hotel, and then diagonally across the rise to our mooring place on the west shore. We have it all to ourselves at present, the other boats preferring to be in the thick of every thin on the east bank. But we have n beautiful sandy beach on which the crew have pitched their tent, and where we instantly established the poultry yard. The three coops were taken from the dahabya put on the sand lld opened. Sir Francis Drake end his three Indies waddled madly for the bank, slid down it on their tails end launches themselves joyously upon the water. The
White Cook stepped daintily forth, lonely but still g~llnnt. All tis \;lives were eaten on the \yay up. But seldom are w!i.do\,hers so soon consoled -by 9 a.m. today he had three more. The turkey cock n. his consort emerged frOID their coop so stiff they could ha:rdl.y stn. up. But they were soon timbered, ant the gobbler strutted end rustled n. gobbled as though he owned the earth.
But Oh my dear! if you could see whe t 1 i e s beyend our ben oh! A grey t plain with stretohes of sand and stretohes of lovely green, and clumps of trees, and then the fierce and glaring n. beautiful Lybian mountnins making a mighty wall beyend. I Cannot give you any idea of how wenderful it is. I could have spent the whole nfternoon looking, but I suddenly went wild with neuralgia in my once end took to my bed and suffered torrents for hours, and then gas suddenly -the pain left end I slept Dll night, and got up this morning ready for Anything. I Waited to go to ohuroh this a.m. but Cousin Emma objected as my once Was still swollen and she snid~fhe ohuroh was always cold.
This afternoon when Cousin Theodore had had his nap, he, Doris, I Red Jones, all in Our riding clothes, were rowed across the river in the felucca. Our donkeys "dere awaiting us in front of the \\Tinter Pad.;oe, the donkey boys (old retainers) kissed Our hands and off we started foe Karnak. We could only take a most cursory look at thus stupendous
ruins -actu~lly inconceivable until you steed in their'presence.
