Sunday afternoon, and on Monday she and Cousin Theodore took their last ride on Julius Caesar and Hermes, -while I had to do the society act for the family, going out to say goodbye to the teachers at the American mission school, and then taking a farewell tea with the Corlessa. That last was quite unnecessary because she left Luxor just as 're did, yesterday and ''''s are all to meet in Cairo. But the poor lady had been ill in bed and was lonely -and I always like to see her. Tuesday Doris and Cousin Emma went over to Luxor early in the morning and I played dominoes. Harry came over from the Valley and spent most of the day. The diggings have stopped (this is the season for stopping them) and Harry \vill join us in Cairo, going down by train in about ten days when he has done the final settling up of everything in the Valley. No. Edgar, Inspector of Excavations in Upper Egypt, says that our discoveries are the only important ones made this winter at Thebes.
Lancelot Crane came to tea that afternoon and he and HarrY and D and 1 can AlwaYs amuse ourselves vastuY tatking to each other. Some ladies Gou sun Emma one".' at so came. And pie son tu Y Grant and HarrY mounted their donkeYs and with a wave of their hats turned towards the vatueY.
lie left Luxor shortly after eleven, I think, yesterday morning and it has gectic getting off. The sands were dotted with natives who had come to say goodhye, and get a parting hackshish, and on the Luxor side, as we passed, tradesmen whom we had patronized, and many friends of the crew waved frantically at us. We have come skiMoing lown thus far -and oh these lovely hanks! They are covered with poppies now in long stretches. We got to Dendereh yesterday afternoon ahout five and stopped for Doris and me to see that temple. Jones said it \"as a very little '.;ask. "A little wCI.lktt in this family means not more than n ten-minute one, so we started on foot. But it had heen some years since Jones had done it and he had forgotten. It WDS almost, if not quite, two miles there, which wouadn't have tattered in the least if it hadn't heen so late. T'\\'o sailors 'vere sent With us, and we wasked us fast as we couad, hut we only got there in time to see the sunset from the roof-Which alone was worth the expedition, and then fairly tore through the dim recesses of the temple and lown into the mhst_umazing crypt. It was so spooky there that it Was comforting to think that the Gaffir -having seen our <athletic go,.rdi'lns at the gates oe the temple -wouad not dare to murder us as he so easily might. It w.ts a 1,'onderful wask hack -qui te recompensing us for the calling do','m that a"'v.ited us. The relatives h;ad grown frightened ahout our heing out 8~ter dark, and here cross in consequence. Of course it was Jones who out to have heen called low -hut considering all Jones does for us I'd always rather take ~ scoading than have him get one. We started out with an escort of two sailors, end we. CRme hack with four sailors (two more having heen sent out to meet us) h,o n,hive men ";ho had attached themselves to the p,'rty,
