Bast beloved -Here \,'s tire vgl\in, heaving finished the voyage down the river Thuesday morning. Said voyage has more or Ie spoiled by the incessant winds which made sitting on deck disagrees and uncomfortable; and sitting on deck is the main point to :~ trip on the Nile. Our running onto the numerous sandbars which now impe navigation in the present low state of the river Doris and I regard as interesting. It was so amusing watching the men get us off. Wednesday morning we sat on a sandbar for an hour in company with 2 large steamers, i small steamer and 27 netive boats!
te are to stay on the boat until a week from today when we move to
Ghezireh Palace. This may sound as though we were to visit the l\.nedive, but it's merely an hotel \~here a hnedivi,R.R pC!place used to and which is run by the same management as Shepheard's. Being on a
