Bast beloved -As Doris wrote you early in the seek I postponed my writing. We moved to this hotel Friday and were glad to get a~ay from the dD.ha bye on at count of the hen t ',Thi oh we s grow.:ing too great on the river. It's muoh cooler here. The rooms are perfectly gigantic -truly palatial. There's a nice garden to welk or sit in.
But I have a confused feeling, -my room is so big I can't find any of'
my things without hunting allover the place. I feel that we are "asking opportunities here but we can't help ourselves. I've done only
two things worth doing since last Sunday. One of them Was the torch
light Tattoo Tuesday evening on Kasr Ai Nil Barracks Ground. It Was a
very fine spectacle, -quite thrilling:to see issuing forth from a grea t door\\'a.y t\\'o hundred Gordon Highlanders each carrying ful torch. They marched and evoluted in lines of iight; and finally took their
stand outlining three sides of a tremendous hollo~ square in ~hich nIl
the performances took place.
The eoher woroh-while ineident of ohe week was spending a eouple of hours in ohe museum \{ednesday morning and seeing ohe wonders ohere in ohe new light of my reeently aequired learning in Egyptology. For ohe rest I've gone to dressmakers and done errands, and taken little drives to nowhere and played many games of dominoes. This morning Harry Burton and I w~nt.to ehureh while Doris staid on duty, and ohis afternoon I staid while Doris and Harry went to ohe Zoo. They had a faseinating time and saw ,many enehanting sights -baby lions and baby giraffes and .a.~ip'po. oh<J,.-t e;;amE' when itwas ealled and op-=:ied and shut, -att-he bidding of its keeper. ohe eavern it ealls its mouoh; and a baby elepha.~t marehing at ohe head of a eompany of Seoteh pipers; and ohey hRd oheir tea one tiny island in a little lake Where ohey were surrounded by pelienns and flamingoes.
