Sunday 6 April, 1913
Ghezireh Palace
Bast beloved -Jones has just informed me that unless I get my letters off at 2:30 this afternoon they won't go for three days. It is now 12:30 and luncheon in half an hour. So this must be dashed off at a gallop. Oh my dear! that camel expedition on Monday was the most wonderful thing I ever did. Of course I was horribly lame for 2 days afterwards, but so were Harry ant Doris. Ya would have adored it, -a'd have given anything to have had you alon/ They weren't awfully good camels either~ so I can imagine the rapture of riding fine ones. Harry went off the other day on an expedition with some English people one of whom was the Major of a Highland regiment. Said Major furnished the camels from the coestguard corps and H'arry ,said they "dere perfectly 'superb, and much much easier to r: than the ones we had. . .
We've haunted bazaars and done errands and had some swagger clothes made (for which your uncle insisted on paying; -but we wouldn't have had them otherwise), and had visitors and tone to teas, and revelled
in street sights, and I've seen the hnedive and almost seen Lord Kitchener but not quite, and have met one of the highest-up men in te Army here -Major ~atson, or Watson Pasha -whichever you choose to
call him, who is aide-de-camp to the Ehedive. He is an enchanting person and if he weren't already married I should try to get him for Little Sister.
We are sailing Wednesday so my next letter will be from Naples where we expect to spend two days, going thence to Florence. No letter
from you since 2 '" eeks ago. Hor;~' all goes wel.1 ,,'ith you. endless
love from ..., Your }.jim
The Mediterranean -10 April, 11] Dampfer "Prinz Heinrich"
Bast beloved. We left Cairo yesterday morning at 9:45 and re~che~ Alexandria at one after a comfortable trip through such lovely scenes I couldn't bear to take my eyes off the windows for a minute. We I sailed at 2:30 and are due in Naples at 11 A.M. Saturday. If we Drei not late and if the day is pleasant (it's funny I remembered to say t that after four months of pleasant days as a matter of course) Herrt is going to take Doris -and me if I can get off ~ to Pompeii. And' Sunday Cousin T. is planning to take us on a marvellous motor trip Do
the coast of Amalfi. Monday we shall probably proceed upon our way to Florence. Before leaving Cairo we managed to work in a little luOre s~gnLseeing. We saw a mosque -the second largest in the world, and quite beautiful. It contains two objects of particular interest a granite column that came there all by itself from }Mecca, and a magic stone which When people have violent tummy aches they go and lick until their tongues bleed. Quite a deep hollow had been licked in it, and the blood stnins on the base were very revolting. We also went to the Tombs of the Caliphs which form a sort of stately City of the Dead with superb domes and exquisite minarets, on the outskirts of the City proper and close to the desert. Doris and I would have given our eyeteeth for one untrammeled "seek in Cairo. There ~Ire such wonderful things to see and do there n. we missed so mnny of them through no fault of ours.
I do so hope to find a letter from you in Naples forwarded from Ports.
It seems very long since I heard.
Your loving, loving Mis.
Grande Bretagne Florence 18 April, 1913
Bast beloved -We are feeling so terribly over the news
of Charlie Wolcott's death which we just heard yesterday. I have
the t most despera te of all feelings -the belief the t someho\<' it m;get
have been prevented. This is no reflection on his father, who could
not drop everything and go with him to California. But if he had had
a mother or his sister to go with him we would not have been subjected
for so long to what Mr. Wolcott himself ~rote me Was "the wrong
treatment." The one say of comfort in the whole tragedy is that he is
now with his mother.
I got your letter of Zarch 20th the other day in Naples, just after I had posted mine to you. And your April 1st one reached me here yesterday. We had to waste one d27 in Naples as it rained so torrentiDl1y~ :J.nc! practically the sele fruit of our stay there ,,"as that Doris se;\' Pompeii -"'hich "gas one of her heart's desires. 1 ":ould have liked to see it too, for in the 30 years which have elapsed since I was there much has been excavated. But it wasn't possible for us both to do it, and I Was crazy to have D. go. We got here Tuesday night, having left Naples at 9:45 that morning, with Vesuvius covered a third of
"the way down from its summit with snow. The cold and the rain here in Italy have been hard to bear after the sunlight and warmth of Egypt. But it is such an entrancing trip here from Naples -such verdant count such beautiful vinyards, such a riot of flo'\'ers, the mount<J.ins and hills so splended and so romantic with the feudal towns crooning the summits of the foothills and long, long roads leading up to them. On the enclosed card I've market about where our sitting room windo~s
are, and the bridge you see MS the far named Ponte Vecchio, lined on both sides with the most enthralling shops. Kaar the bridge this side of the Ponte Vecchio, and Which just masses getting into the picture, someone was committing suicide as we drove up to the hotel the night of our arrival.
