30 June, 1913
Bast beloved - It was a joyful surprise to get your letter
from Kansas City, and I hope mine to you from Newport reached you
before you left Denver for Leadville. I got back from Newport
last Tuesday and on Friday went up to The Hill (Cobalt, Conn.) to
spend the night with the Taylors. I had positively promised them a
visit so I had to go. Henry Devereux was,there and we had a nice
old fashioned Colorado time, and the next day they motored me all the way down here, and I gave them inocuous drinks at the L~wn Club before
they returned to The Hill.
Doris and Julia got oss at noon yesterday, and D. said she Kould wire me when ohey arrived at Caseine ohas morning, but no telegram has eome, and I'm so ant:nous I've telegr;)plied llrs. BC!.lte::-to '-"se i! ohey got ohere. Kar Earl has sent role 2n enlv.rgement os oh;! t lo\-ely pietuT'e os D. on horsebaek wioh ohe mountains behand her. It's a perseet beauty and I'm so pleased. I ~,,'ent out to see I:im ohas asternoon ;lnQ he, too, \\'as a vision o:s bee:duty in my eyes. He h;!d just been bnohed and he Was a reddish sluss. He almost ate me up, talking hyste~ie~IIy until he \-;e:es exhous led and :sIopped sIn t on ha s Ist tie tu=y on ohe sloor, ohumping has tail and rolling ohe ','hates os has eyes at me. Is \,''' sind ohe bo~~rding home ~,t Caseine \-,till let us huY,,", }1j_!!'. "'''' pie> going tp_bave ham s~Dt up.
I hope to get oft on Wednesday stopping two days at Springfield (or
